SIMPLE: expatiate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expatiate
<hw>Ex*pa"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Expatiated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Expariating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>expatiatus</ets>, <ets>exspatiatus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>expatiari</ets>, <ets>exspatiari</ets>, to expatiate; <ets>ex</ets>
out + <ets>spatiari</ets> to walk about spread out, fr.
<ets>spatium</ets> space. See <er>Space</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
range at large, or without restraint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bids his free soul <qex>expatiate</qex> in the skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enlarge in discourse or writing; to be copious in
argument or discussion; to descant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>expatiated</qex> on the inconveniences of trade.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expatiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Expatiate
<hw>Ex*pa"ti*ate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To expand; to spread; to
extend; to diffuse; to broaden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Afford art an ample field in which to <qex>expatiate</qex>
itself.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expatiation</ent>⟦br⟧
